==English==

===Alternative forms===
* {{l|en|hippety-hop}}

===Etymology===
Compound of *''hippity'' + {{m|en|hop}}, in turn from {{suffix|en|hip|-ety|pos1=a regional variant of ''hop''}}. Attested since the middle nineteenth century, with {{m|en|hippity-hoppity}} appearing somewhat earlier.

===Adjective===
{{en-adj|more}}

# {{lb|en|childish}} Moving by [[hop]]ping, having an uneven [[gait]].
#* {{quote-book|lang=en|1987|G. Bennett|Birdfinding in Canada|https://www.worldcat.org/title/birdfinding-in-canada/oclc/9084915|21|There must be hundreds of them killed every summer day - and, it's no wonder when one observes the erratic, '''hippity-hop''' way they try to cross the road.}}
# {{lb|en|figurative}} Proceeding through uneven stages.
#* {{quote-book|lang=en|1976|Bill Hosokawa|Thunder in the Rockies: The Incredible Denver Post||133|In 1927, when United Air Lines began service over a '''hippity-hop''' route between San Francisco and Chicago, Cheyenne again rather than Denver was picked as a stop.}}

===Adverb===
{{en-adv|-}}

# {{lb|en|childish}} Unevenly, with a hopping gait.
#* {{quote-book|lang=en|1857|John Edward Taylor|The Fairy Ring: A Collection of Tales and Traditions, Translated from the German of Jacob and Wilhelm Grimm||101|So he mounted the horse, which went '''hippity-hop''', '''hippity-hop'''.|chapter=The Wild Man}}
#* {{quote-book|lang=en|1938|Elizabeth Baker|Language Journeys with our Friends||109|Which show how the tortoise moved? hopped / waddled / scampered / scurried / plodded / ran '''hippity-hop''' / took one slow step after another}}

====Usage notes====
* Frequently used with the verb ''[[go]]'': "He went hippity-hop all the way down the hill."

